liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Members of the Greens have walked out of parliament chambers in a fiery protest against Labor's position on the Israel-Gaza war. Greens Deputy Leader Mehreen Faruqi led what she labelled the "people's protest" inside parliament during Senate question time. "You are watching the massacre of thousands of Palestinians by Israel and you are not condemning Israel," Ms Faruqi said. "You refuse to call for an immediate ceasefire. "We are not going to sit here and watch you pat yourselves on the back for doing nothing." Ms Faruqi and her colleagues then left the chambers despite repeated calls for order. Prime Minister Anthony Albanese has demonstrated support for Israel since Hamas's terrorist attack on Southern Israel on October 7 while expressing concern for Gaza civilians.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: 'Free Palestine': Greens members walk out of Senate chambers in protest

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Jordan's King Abdullah says Jordan's air force personnel have "air-dropped at midnight urgent medical aid to the Jordanian field hospital in Gaza". He said it is Jordan's duty and that it would always stand with Palestinians. "A royal air force plane dropped urgent medical aid using parachutes to the Jordanian field hospital in Gaza whose supplies were about to run out due to the delay of delivering aid through Rafah crossing", Jordan's state news agency said citing a military source in the General Command of the Jordanian Armed Forces. After signing a peace treaty 30 years ago, Jordan and Israel have had a good political relationship, however with the current escalation the government has faced pressure to not only express their solidarity with Palestinians, but to take action. The King and Queen have criticised Israel's actions in Gaza and called for an immediate cease fire and Jordan's ambassador was recalled while the Israeli ambassador was told to stay away. You can read more about the challenges Jordan now faces here:

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Earlier we reported that Lebanese authorities said an Israeli strike on a car in south Lebanon killed three children and their grandmother. Now in a statement, Hezbollah said it would never tolerate attacks on civilians and its response would be "firm and strong". "The enemy will pay the price for its crimes against civilians," Hezbollah lawmaker Hassan Fadlallah told Reuters. Footage broadcast by television station al-Mayadeen showed rescue workers removing one of the casualties from the still-smouldering remains of the car. Israel's military said its troops engaged a vehicle "identified as a suspected transport for terrorists" in Lebanon, and it was looking into reports there were civilians inside. Lebanon's caretaker Prime Minister Najib Mikati called it a "heinous crime." Foreign Minister Abdallah Bou Habib told Reuters Lebanon would submit a complaint to the United Nations over the killing of civilians, including children, in the attack. For a deeper dive into the history of Hezbollah, Matt Bevan takes a look at how they were created: Or you can read our explainer here:

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: While there were some interesting individual moves, the market overall was pretty stable today. It was around 0.3% higher in early trade and the ASX 200 closed 0.3% higher at 6,997 points. Healthcare was the frontrunner all day, closing up 1.7%. Sector giant CSL finished 1.7% up at $248.22, rebounding from recent weakness, while Resmed had an even better 3.1% rise to $23.87. Consumer cyclical stocks had a good day, after bets on US rate rises fell even further on Friday, taking some pressure off rate increases globally. Despite this, bets on a Reserve Bank of Australia cash rate rise tomorrow at 2:30pm AEDT continue to hover just below 60%. Utilities and financial stocks also had a good day, with Westpac's 26% rise in profit and $1.5 billion share buyback prompting a 2 per cent rise for its share price to $21.92, with the rest of the big four up between 0.5 and 1 per cent. Industrials, energy and mining were all down, although gold miners were amongst the best gainers, with South32 (-1.5%) and Rio Tinto (-0.9%) two of the major drags. Biggest gains: Iress +8.3% to $5.64 De Grey Mining +7.4% to $1.23 Lovisa Holdings +5.1% to $19.43 Evolution Mining +5.1% to $3.69 Bellevue Gold +4.8% to $1.43 Biggest losses: Block -6.3% to $76.10 Paladin Energy -5% to $0.955 Karoon Energy -3.2% to $2.44 Lynas Rare Earths -3.1% to $6.99 Computershare -2.9% to $24.41 That's it from me for today. Please join David Chau and Kate Ainsworth on the blog tomorrow for a very busy rates day!
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: A steady gain for the ASX ahead of rates day tomorrow

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: A former Qantas executive says the airline's management has a lot of work to do if it wants to keep investors before its next annual general meeting with shareholders next year. Shareholders showed their discontent at last week's AGM, delivering the airline its first strike with an overwhelming 83% protest vote against its executive pay report. If shareholders deliver a second protest vote against the remuneration report at next year's AGM, Qantas's board faces a potential spill. Aviation consultant Andrew Charlton is a former chief legal officer for Qantas, and says shareholders have put the airline's executives on notice. "They've now got effectively 12 months to come back to the next AGM and say 'right, we're back' ... and I'm really interested in how they're going to do that," he said. "Frankly I'm not convinced that just doing more of the same, which at the moment seems to be the blueprint, is going to get them there." You can listen to his full interview with Hamish Macdonald on RN Breakfast this morning below:
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Former Qantas exec says 'more of the same' from management won't satisfy shareholders
